f vitamin K antagonists?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Directly inhibits activated clotting factors","Prevents vitamin K-dependent gamma-carboxylation of clotting factors","Increases the breakdown of existing clotting factors","Blocks calcium binding sites on all clotting factors","Prevents the synthesis of vitamin K in the liver"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EVitamin K antagonists like warfarin work by \u003Cstrong\u003Epreventing vitamin K-dependent gamma-carboxylation of clotting factors\u003C/strong\u003E. This modification is essential for factors II, VII, IX, and X to bind calcium and participate in the coagulation cascade.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect inhibition of activated clotting factors\u003C/strong\u003E is not how vitamin K antagonists work, as they do not interact with existing activated factors. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking calcium binding sites on all clotting factors\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because vitamin K antagonists only affect vitamin K-dependent factors, not the entire coagulation cascade. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing the breakdown of existing clotting factors\u003C/strong\u003E is not the mechanism, as these drugs do not affect the degradation rate of clotting factors. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPreventing the synthesis of vitamin K in the liver\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because vitamin K antagonists block vitamin K recycling rather than its synthesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe anticoagulant effect develops gradually over several days as existing functional clotting factors must be depleted and replaced by dysfunctional ones that cannot bind calcium.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vitamin K antagonists like warfarin work by inhibiting vitamin K epoxide reductase, preventing the activation of clotting factors II, VII, IX, and X.","Vitamin K is essential for the gamma-carboxylation of clotting factors which enables them to bind calcium and participate in coagulation.","The anticoagulant effect of vitamin K antagonists takes several days to develop as existing functional clotting factors must be depleted."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52325"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16769"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52325","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52325"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-03T07:28:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-03T07:32:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9460"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66871"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes